<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 17 日星期一 04:00:54 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Europeans Are Becoming Poorer. ‘Yes, We’re All Worse Off.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>重视空闲时间的人口老龄化为经济停滞奠定了基础。然后是 Covid-19 和俄罗斯在乌克兰的战争。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817790/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="巴黎的一家餐厅。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>巴黎的一家餐厅。西里尔·马西尔哈西/彭博新闻<span>西里尔·马西尔哈西/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-fairless" itemprop="url" rel="author">汤姆·费尔莱斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日上午 12:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>欧洲人正面临着几十年来从未经历过的新经济现实。他们变得越来越穷。</p><p>随着欧洲人的购买力逐渐消失，长期以来因其<em>生活艺术而</em>被外人羡慕的大陆上的生活正在迅速失去光彩。</p><p>法国人正在少吃鹅肝，少喝红酒。西班牙人对橄榄油很吝啬。芬兰人被敦促在大风天使用桑拿浴室，因为那时能源价格较低。在整个德国，肉类和牛奶的消费量已降至三十年来的最低水平，一度繁荣的有机食品市场也陷入了低迷。意大利经济发展部长阿道夫·乌尔索（Adolfo Urso）于五月召开了一次危机会议，讨论该国最受欢迎的主食意大利面的价格，此前意大利面的价格上涨了全国通胀率的两倍多。</p><p>随着消费支出直线下降，欧洲在年初陷入衰退，强化了本世纪初开始出现的经济、政治和军事相对衰退的感觉。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="960" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818002?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>欧洲当前的困境由来已久。人口老龄化导致人们对空闲时间和工作保障的重视超过了收入，导致经济和生产力增长多年来一直乏善可陈。然后是Covid-19大流行和俄罗斯在乌克兰的旷日持久的战争的一对二重击。这场危机颠覆了全球供应链，导致能源和食品价格飙升，加剧了数十年来持续恶化的疾病。</p><p>政府的反应只会让问题更加复杂化。为了保住就业机会，他们主要向雇主提供补贴，导致消费者在价格冲击来临时没有现金缓冲。相比之下，美国人受益于廉价的能源和主要针对公民以保持消费的政府援助。</p><p>过去，非洲大陆强大的出口工业可能会起到拯救作用。但作为欧洲的重要市场，中国的缓慢复苏正在削弱这一增长支柱。高能源成本和自 20 世纪 70 年代以来从未见过的严重通货膨胀正在削弱制造商在国际市场上的价格优势，并破坏非洲大陆曾经和谐的劳资关系。随着全球贸易降温，欧洲对出口的严重依赖（出口占欧元区 GDP 的 50% 左右，而美国仅占 10%）正在成为一个弱点。</p><p>根据经济合作与发展组织（总部位于巴黎、主要由富裕国家组成的俱乐部）的数据，自 2019 年底以来，经过通货膨胀调整后，欧元区 20 国的私人消费下降了约 1%。在美国，劳动力市场强劲且收入不断增加，家庭收入增长了近9%。欧盟目前约占全球消费支出的 18%，而美国这一比例为 28%。十五年前，欧盟和美国各占总数的约四分之一。</p><p>根据通货膨胀和购买力进行调整后，德国的工资自 2019 年以来下降了约 3%，意大利和西班牙下降了 3.5%，希腊下降了 6%。根据经合组织的数据，同期美国的实际工资增长了约 6%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817793?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名老妇人离开柏林教堂的食品分发中心。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马库斯·施赖伯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这种痛苦波及到了中产阶级。最近的一个晚上，在欧洲最富有的城市之一布鲁塞尔，教师和护士排队从卡车后面领取半价杂货。供应商欢乐时光市场从超市收集接近保质期的食物，并通过应用程序进行广告。顾客可以在下午早些时候下订单，并在晚上领取打折的杂货。</p><p> “有些顾客告诉我，因为你，我每周可以吃两到三次肉，”正在分发一箱箱杂货的皮埃尔·范赫德说。</p><p> 33 岁的护士卡里姆·布阿扎 (Karim Bouazza) 正在为妻子和两个孩子储备半价肉和鱼，他抱怨说，通货膨胀意味着“你几乎需要做第二份工作来支付一切费用”。</p><p>类似的服务在该地区如雨后春笋般涌现，将自己宣传为减少食物浪费和省钱的一种方式。 TooGoodToGo 是一家于 2015 年在丹麦成立的公司，销售零售商和餐馆的剩余食物，在欧洲拥有 7600 万注册用户，大约是 2020 年底人数的三倍。在德国，2017 年创建的初创公司 Sirplus 提供“在其在线商店中拯救“食品，包括过期的产品。 Motatos 也是如此，它于 2014 年在瑞典创立，目前已进军芬兰、德国、丹麦和英国</p><p>高端杂货的支出大幅下降。 2022年，德国人均肉类消费量为52公斤，比上一年减少约8%，是自1989年开始计算以来的最低水平。虽然其中部分反映了社会对健康饮食和动物福利的担忧，但专家表示，这一趋势正在加速近几个月来肉类价格上涨了30%。据联邦农业信息中心称，德国人也正在将牛肉和小牛肉等肉类换成家禽等较便宜的肉类。</p><p>法兰克福附近的有机食品供应商托马斯·沃尔夫 (Thomas Wolff) 表示，由于通货膨胀飙升，去年他的销售额下降了 30%。沃尔夫表示，他在疫情爆发初期雇佣了 33 名员工来应对对昂贵生态食品的强劲需求，但后来他将他们全部解雇。</p><p> 26 岁的汉堡顾问兼作家 Ronja Ebeling 表示，她将大约四分之一的收入储蓄起来，部分原因是她担心没有足够的钱养老。她在衣服或化妆品上花的钱很少，并与伴侣的父亲共用一辆车。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817996?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>消费疲软和人口前景不佳，使得欧洲对消费品巨头<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PG" class="company-name">宝洁公司和</a>奢侈品帝国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LVMUY" class="">路威酩轩集团</a>等企业的吸引力下降<span class="company-name-type">，</span>这些公司在北美的销售额所占份额越来越大。</p><p> “美国消费者比欧洲消费者更有弹性，”<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UL" class="">联合利华</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span></p>首席财务官 Graeme Pitkethly 在四月份表示。<p></p><p>国际货币基金组织的数据显示，以美元计算，过去 15 年欧元区经济增长了约 6%，而美国的增长率为 82%。总部位于布鲁塞尔的独立智囊团欧洲国际政治经济中心本月发布的一份报告显示，这使得欧盟国家的人均收入比除爱达荷州和密西西比州以外的美国各州都要贫困。报告称，如果目前的趋势持续下去，到2035年，美国和欧盟的人均经济产出差距将与今天的日本和厄瓜多尔之间的差距一样大。</p><p>马略卡岛商会旅游委员会主席玛丽亚·弗龙特拉表示，在地中海岛屿马略卡岛，企业正在游说增加飞往美国的航班，以增加自由消费的美国游客数量。美国人平均每天在酒店花费约 260 欧元（292 美元），而欧洲人每天在酒店的花费不到 180 欧元（202 美元）。</p><p> “今年，由于我们面临的经济形势，我们看到欧洲人的行为发生了巨大变化，”最近前往迈阿密学习如何更好地迎合美国客户的弗龙特拉说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="789" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817781?width=1260&amp;height=789" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">人们在马略卡岛萨雷纳尔海滨度假胜地的海滩酒吧享受温暖的气温。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Clara Margais/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>增长疲软和利率上升正在给欧洲慷慨的福利国家带来压力，而这些国家提供受欢迎的医疗服务和养老金。欧洲各国政府发现解决问题的旧方法要么变得难以承受，要么已经不再有效。四分之三万亿欧元的补贴、税收减免和其他形式的减免已经流向消费者和企业，以抵消能源成本上升——经济学家表示，这本身就加剧了通货膨胀，违背了补贴的目的。</p><p>全球金融危机后公共支出的削减导致欧洲国家资助的医疗保健系统，尤其是英国的国家医疗服务体系陷入饥饿。</p><p> Vivek Trivedi 是一位居住在英国曼彻斯特的 31 岁麻醉师，每周工作 48 小时，年薪约为 51,000 英镑（67,000 美元）。他说，近一年来英国的通货膨胀率一直在 10% 左右或更高，这正在吞噬他的每月预算。特里维迪说，他在折扣零售商处购买杂货，外出就餐的花费较少。他说，一些同事近几个月来完全关闭了暖气，担心他们无法承受大幅上涨的成本。</p><p> 28 岁的伦敦公共事务专家诺亚·科恩 (Noa Cohen) 表示，通过利用美国护照跨越大西洋，她可以在同样的工作中使自己的薪水翻两番。科恩最近在换工作后获得了10%的加薪，但涨幅完全被通货膨胀所吞噬。她说，朋友们正在冷冻卵子，因为他们短期内无力抚养孩子，希望将来有足够的钱。</p><p> “感觉就像生活水平永久冻结，”她说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818000?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>英国央行首席经济学家休·皮尔（Huw Pill）四月份警告英国公民，他们需要接受自己变得更穷的事实，并停止推动更高的工资。 “是的，我们的情况都变得更糟了，”他说，并表示寻求通过提高工资来抵消物价上涨只会加剧通胀。</p><p>由于欧洲各国政府需要增加国防开支，且借贷成本不断上升，经济学家预计税收将增加，从而增加消费者的压力。相对于其他富裕国家，欧洲的税收已经很高，相当于 GDP 的 40-45% 左右，而美国则为 27%。美国工人几乎四分之三的工资带回家，包括所得税和社会保障税，而法国和德国工人只得到一半。</p><p>欧洲的贫困化增强了工会队伍的实力，工会在整个欧洲大陆吸纳了数万名会员，扭转了长达数十年的衰退趋势。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817780?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英国央行一直在加息以对抗通胀。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾森·奥尔登/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>更高的工会化程度可能不会为会员带来更充足的收入。这是因为，即使在技能短缺不断加剧的情况下，许多人仍在推动工人更愿意拥有更多的空闲时间而不是更高的工资。</p><p>德国最大的工会 IG Metall 呼吁在今年 11 月的集体谈判谈判之前，德国金属工人在目前的工资水平上每周工作四天，而不是加薪。官员们表示，缩短工作周将改善工人的健康和生活质量，同时使该行业对年轻工人更具吸引力。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对欧洲经济健康状况有何看法？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>德国联合服务工会主席 Frank Werneke 表示，德国医疗保健行业近一半的员工选择每周工作 30 小时左右，而不是全职工作，这反映出工作条件恶劣，该国联合服务工会近几个月新增了约 11 万名新会员。创22年来最大增幅。</p><p>芬兰北部的游戏开发商 Kristian Kallio 最近决定将每周工作时间减少五分之一至 30 小时，以换取 10% 的减薪。他现在每月赚取约 2,500 欧元。 “谁不想缩短工作时间呢？”卡利奥说道。卡利奥的老板雅科·基尔马奥贾 (Jaakko Kylmäoja) 表示，尽管领导者都是全职工作，但他的同事中约有三分之一接受了同样的协议。</p><p> Kallio 现在的工作时间是上午 10 点到下午 4.30。他利用额外的空闲时间发展自己的爱好，比如做饭和骑长途自行车。 “我不认为我会回到正常工作时间，”他说。</p><p>伊戈尔·柴科夫斯基 (Igor Chaykovskiy) 是一名 34 岁的巴黎 IT 工人，今年早些时候加入了一个工会，要求提高工资和工作条件。他最近获得了 3.5% 的加薪，大约是通货膨胀水平的一半。他认为工会将给予工人更大的压力来向经理施压。不过，这不仅仅是薪酬问题。 “也许他们说你的工资没有增加，你有免费的体育课或音乐课，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="837" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817792?width=1260&amp;height=837" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马蒂亚斯·森恩（右）是德国富裕的黑森林地区的一名屠夫，他找不到当地的求职者来替代四名准备退休的工人，因此他聘请了一名来自印度的学徒 Rajakumar Bheemappa Lamani。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的多米尼克·纳尔 (Dominic Nahr)</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>意大利金属工人工会的工会成员马可·洛米奥表示，在意大利南部梅尔菲的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/STLA" class="company-name">Stellantis</a>汽车工厂，由于原材料采购困难和能源成本高昂，近年来员工的工作时间不断缩短。最近工作时间减少了约 30%，工资也相应减少。</p><p>洛米奥说：“在高通胀和工人能源成本上涨之间，很难承担所有家庭开支。”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629<author><![CDATA[Tom Fairless]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Investors Are Bailing on Cathie Wood’s ARK Fund]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>曾经最大的主动管理型 ETF，该基金规模已缩水至约 90 亿美元<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001049381"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815749?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cathie Wood 于 2014 年推出了 ARK Innovation ETF。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布伦丹·麦克德米德/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001049381"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jack-pitcher" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰克·皮彻</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 16 日下午 2:24（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-are-bailing-on-cathie-woods-popular-ark-fund-dbf5d801"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Cathie Wood 的旗舰 ETF 今年已上涨 50% 以上。投资者正在利用这一机会退出。</p><p>据 FactSet 称，过去 12 个月，他们已从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/etf/ARKK">ARK Innovation ETF</a>净撤资 7.17 亿美元。对于自 2014 年成立以来一直吸引投资者现金的基金来说，这次资金外流标志着一个显着的转变。该基金曾经是规模最大的主动管理型 ETF，管理资产近 300 亿美元，但目前已缩水至约 90 亿美元，主要原因是投资损失。</p><p>伍德的基金以其股票代码 ARKK 闻名，在 Covid-19 大流行爆发后不久，该基金就成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cathie-wood-is-wall-streets-hottest-hand-maybe-too-hot-11612544044?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">投资者的宠儿</a>，对无利可图和“颠覆性”科技公司的押注取得了巨大成功。它吸收了大量投资者资金，最终在 2021 年第一季度流入 65 亿美元，当时其股价达到顶峰。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815576?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>然后，美联储数十年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/feds-powell-suggested-july-rate-rise-is-likely-analysts-say-6ae8ee77?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最快的加息行动</a>压垮了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cathie-woods-ark-faces-test-as-tech-rally-cools-11615208809?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">无法盈利的成长型公司</a>的估值，这些公司通常在利率较低且CD等更安全的投资回报率极低时吸引投资者。 ARKK 的股价在 2022 年暴跌 67%，但其投资者基本上持有或买入了下跌的股票。现在，分析师表示，他们预计其中一些投资者将永远退出。</p><p>塔特尔资本管理公司(Tuttle Capital Management)首席执行官马修·塔特尔(Matthew Tuttle)表示，“有一整群人进入了接近顶峰的位置，却遭受了可怕的损失。”塔特尔资本管理公司经营着一只反向ETF，让投资者可以做空伍德的基金。 “我想其中一些人说过，‘我永远也回不到平衡；’”这可能是我能做的最好的事情了，是时候离开了。”</p><p>伍德表示，与该基金的资产相比，资金外流规模很小。</p><p> “自 21 年 2 月以来，我们对资产保留情况感到惊讶，”伍德在接受采访时表示。 “这一数字占资产的比例非常小，这表明，与那些在长期低迷时期留在基金中的人相比，获利的人更有可能获利。”</p><p>尽管最近有所上涨，但 ARKK 股价仍比历史高点低约 70%。由于人们希望美联储的紧缩政策即将结束，标准普尔 500 指数今年已上涨 17%；较 2022 年初的高点仍下跌 6.1%。</p><p> ARKK 持股​​前五名分别是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">Tesla</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/COIN" class="">Coinbase Global</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ROKU" class="">Roku</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ZM" class="company-name">Zoom Video Communications</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SQ" class="">Block</a> <span class="company-name-type">。</span>去年只有特斯拉和 Zoom 实现盈利。特斯拉在该基金中持有 11% 的股份，为该基金今年的上涨提供了动力。这家电动汽车制造商的股价在 2023 年增长了一倍多，但与 ARKK 一样，股价较之前的高点大幅下跌。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815274?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>尽管科技股今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-funds-rally-12-4-gain-2023-cbe84472?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">强势回归</a>，但表现最好的大多是成熟、盈利且能产生大量现金的公司，例如微软和亚马逊。与两年前不同，投资者似乎对那些预计要在未来几年才能盈利的公司失去了兴趣和耐心。较高的利率意味着等待盈利的机会成本要高得多。</p><p> CFRA Research ETF 数据和分析主管 Aniket Ullal 表示：“与 ARK 基金表现良好时相比，市场情绪肯定发生了变化。” “ETF持有的许多股票在未来退出之前不会有大量现金流，而且这是一个更具挑战性的环境，预计利率将在更长时间内保持较高水平。”</p><p>投资者表示，ARK 品牌在该基金大幅下跌后失去了光彩。在错过了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达</a>股价<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-is-still-a-buy-on-wall-street-as-analysts-race-to-boost-price-targets-964e6ec7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大幅上涨的</a>机会后<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司再次遭受打击。英伟达是一家图形芯片制造商，处于人工智能技术热潮的核心。 ARKK 在 1 月份出售了其最后持有的 Nvidia 股份，该股份长期以来一直是其最大的持股之一。 Nvidia 是今年标准普尔 500 指数中表现最好的公司，股价上涨了两倍多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815772?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">芯片制造商英伟达的股价今年飙升。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：I-Hwa Cheng/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“玫瑰的花朵有点脱落，”塔特尔说。</p><p>伍德表示，过去两年的负面宣传为 ARK 提供了一个机会，巩固其作为专注于颠覆性创新的资产管理公司的品牌。</p><p> “我可以告诉你，在 20 世纪末和 21 年初，当我们不能做任何错事而人们只是在追逐时，我感到非常不舒服，”她说。 “今天，我感觉很舒服。我们没有看到这种行为。这告诉我，外面有一堵担忧之墙。这通常会维持牛市。”</p><p> ARK 的资金流出即将到来，而 ETF 投资者似乎渴望将资金投入其他基金。道富银行的数据显示，6 月份是自 10 月份以来股票 ETF 资金流入最好的月份，而主动型基金当月吸引了 100 亿美元的资金流入，过去 12 个月吸引了超过 1000 亿美元的资金流入。</p><p>马修·巴托里尼 (Matthew Bartolini) 表示，投资者表现出“孩子般的热情”，并“双脚跳入市场的反弹”。</p>道富银行 ETF 业务美洲研究主管在一份研究报告中表示。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817934?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> FactSet 的数据显示，自成立以来，ARKK 基金的平均年化回报率为 11%，但按美元加权年化计算，ARKK 投资者的平均回报率为 21%。</p><p> “ARKK 股东没有把握好购买时机。许多人高价买进，但尚未卖出。”FactSet 全球基金研究总监伊丽莎白·卡什纳 (Elisabeth Kashner) 表示。</p><p>该基金仍然是伍德的摇钱树，伍德拥有其母公司 ARK Investment Management 的多数股权。其0.75%的年费约为主动ETF平均费用的两倍。</p><p>尽管费用收入远低于 2021 年的峰值，但 ARKK 今年的费用已超过 2000 万美元。根据 FactSet 的分析，ARK Investment Management 目前在至少 145 个不同发行人中的主动股票 ETF 日收入中排名第三。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对 Cathie Wood 的 ARK 基金看涨还是看跌？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>可以肯定的是，ARKK 旗下许多以科技为主的股票的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-news-today-04-19-2023/card/cathie-wood-touts-exponential-long-term-growth-opportunities-as-ark-funds-outperform-Z6nb17vLAckBAVl8pgwF?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">市场复苏</a>令许多人感到惊讶，凸显了试图预测业绩的危险。</p><p> Envestnet 联席首席投资官达纳·德奥里亚 (Dana D&#39;Auria) 表示：“如果你只看利率，你就不会预料到今年经济增长会出现如此大的反弹。” “这是一个了解市场预测为何不起作用的经典窗口。谁会想到人工智能会蓬勃发展并引起如此巨大的兴趣？”</p><p>写信给杰克·皮彻<a href="mailto:jack.pitcher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jack.pitcher@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 18:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-are-bailing-on-cathie-woods-popular-ark-fund-dbf5d801</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-are-bailing-on-cathie-woods-popular-ark-fund-dbf5d801<author><![CDATA[Jack Pitcher]]></author><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>投资建议/研究服务</category><category>交易所交易基金</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> ARK创新ETF</category><category>阿尔克</category><category>凯西·伍德</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>投资建议</category><category>研究服务</category><category>交易所交易基金</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Jane Birkin, the Singer Who Inspired the Hermès Bag, Dies at 76]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Birkin 于 20 世纪 60 年代末在法国取得了成功，其中最著名的是与 Serge Gainsbourg 的合作<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817991/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="歌手兼女演员简·伯金 (Jane Birkin) 出席 2021 年戛纳电影节。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>歌手兼女演员简·伯金 (Jane Birkin) 出席 2021 年戛纳电影节。 valery hach​​e/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>valery hach​​e/法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001058530"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001058530"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ginger-adamsotis" itemprop="url" rel="author">姜格·亚当斯·奥蒂斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 16 日下午 1:21（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jane-birkin-actress-singer-who-inspired-the-iconic-hermes-bag-dies-at-76-ce57033b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>英国出生的女演员兼歌手简·伯金 (Jane Birkin) 于周日去世，她在 20 世纪 60 年代末声名鹊起，并为以她命名的标志性<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FR/XPAR/RMS" class="company-name">爱马仕</a>手袋提供了灵感。她已经76岁了。</p><p>柏金 (Birkin) 在伦敦长大，但在法国成名。她年轻时搬到那里，遇到了法国演员兼歌手塞尔日·甘斯布（Serge Gainsbourg），两人有着长期的浪漫和创意合作。</p><p>两人经常在专业上合作，并于 1969 年发行了“Je t&#39;aime…moi non plus”，这是他们最热门的音乐作品之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817993?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1976 年，塞尔日·甘斯布 (Serge Gainsbourg) 和简·伯金 (Jane Birkin) 在法国戛纳。两人有着长期的浪漫关系，并在创意项目上进行了合作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="851" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818045?width=1260&amp;height=851" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 20 世纪 60 年代初的简·伯金 (Jane Birkin)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：McKeown/Daily Express/Hulton Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> 1983年，在一次飞行中，柏金坐在爱马仕董事长旁边，当时她的草包打开了。伯金 (Birkin) 育有三个孩子，她也面临着寻找一款能够容纳忙碌的职业母亲所需一切物品的包袋的挑战。</p><p>这次谈话促成了柏金包的诞生，这是名人和时尚爱好者梦寐以求的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hermes-birkin-diy-handbag-leather-maker-tiktok-144e93fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">身份象征、奢华手提包</a>。</p><p>柏金包有不同的皮革材质，价格从大约 10,000 美元到六位数不等。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817999?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">爱马仕 Birkin 手提包以这位英国出生的女演员兼歌手的名字命名。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：杰里米·莫勒/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>伯金在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jane-birkin-forgot-her-lines-but-landed-her-first-acting-gig-anyway-11620138659?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021 年接受《华尔街日报》采访时表示，</a>她没有使用爱马仕包，尽管它的灵感来自于她。</p><p> “我带的东西太多了，而且太重了。我把东西塞进外套口袋里，”她当时说道。</p><p>法国文化部<a href="https://twitter.com/MinistereCC/status/1680548519822651392?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">在社交媒体上分享的</a>一份声明中表示，伯金是“永恒的法语偶像”。该部表示，除了甘斯布之外，伯金还与其他法国伟人合作过，包括歌手兼词曲作者艾蒂安·达霍和电影制片人阿涅斯·瓦尔达。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818005?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1974 年的简·伯金 (Jane Birkin)。她在伦敦长大，但在法国成名。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：RALPH GATTI/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这位女演员在她的职业生涯中出演了瓦尔达和米开朗基罗·安东尼奥尼等导演的数十部电影。</p><p>伯金在伦敦一个富有创意、舒适的中产阶级家庭中长大，1965 年与英国作曲家兼指挥家约翰·巴里 (John Barry) 结婚。他们后来离婚，但育有一个女儿，时尚摄影师凯特·巴里 (Kate Barry)，她于 2013 年去世。</p><p>伯金还有另外两个女儿：歌手兼演员夏洛特·甘斯布 (Charlotte Gainsbourg)，是她与塞尔日·甘斯布 (Serge Gainsbourg) 生下的女儿<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303562904579228150042814862?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">；法国模特兼歌手卢·</a>杜瓦隆 (Lou Doillon)，是与法国电影导演兼编剧雅克·杜瓦隆 (Jacques Doillon) 生下的女儿。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818043?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1999 年，简·伯金（中）和她的两个女儿卢·杜永 (Lou Doillon) 和夏洛特·甘斯布 (Charlotte Gainsbourg)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Bertrand Rindoff Petroff/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Ginger Adams Otis，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Ginger.AdamsOtis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ginger.AdamsOtis@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 17:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/jane-birkin-actress-singer-who-inspired-the-iconic-hermes-bag-dies-at-76-ce57033b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/jane-birkin-actress-singer-who-inspired-the-iconic-hermes-bag-dies-at-76-ce57033b<author><![CDATA[Ginger Adams Otis]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category>消费品</category><category>奢侈品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>爱马仕国际SCA</category><category>均方根频率</category><category>频率：有效值</category><category>爱马仕</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>消费品</category><category>奢侈品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Europeans Grow More Assertive on Ukraine as Washington Shows Caution]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>北约峰会凸显了关于乌克兰在联盟中的未来以及西方在武器供应方面应走多远的分歧<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001058400"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817983?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在立陶宛举行的北约峰会新闻发布会之前，一面乌克兰国旗被带到舞台上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Beata Zawrzel/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001058400"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/yaroslav-trofimov" itemprop="url" rel="author">雅罗斯拉夫·特罗菲莫夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 11:11（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/changing-places-europeans-grow-more-assertive-on-ukraine-as-washington-shows-caution-e4b83acf"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>立陶宛维尔纽斯——上周的北约峰会揭示了美国领导的跨大西洋联盟内部的重大调整。</p><p>曾经被认为对基辅的支持不够坚定、更容易受到俄罗斯压力的欧洲国家决心帮助乌克兰赢得明确的胜利。与此同时，拜登政府去年对俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京( <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> )的入侵精心策划了西方的统一反应，但受到国内政治和对与莫斯科直接对抗的恐惧的限制， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fearing-russian-escalation-some-nato-allies-favor-hazier-line-on-ukraine-108ef040?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">变得越来越谨慎</a>。</p><p>在欧洲，不同国家首都之间一度悬殊的分歧已大幅缩小，此前被视为对俄罗斯态度软弱的国家，包括法国、意大利、西班牙以及较小程度上的德国，都变得更加接近乌克兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-ukraine-war-at-its-doorstep-poland-becomes-wests-firebrand-3c33d27?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最激烈的支持者</a>：波兰、波罗的海和北欧国家。</p><p> “这花了一段时间，但随后它就渗透了出来。如今，包括德国在内的许多欧洲领导人都明白，如果他们想捍卫自身安全，就必须帮助乌克兰击败普京。”欧洲议会德国议员莱因哈德·布蒂科费尔 (Reinhard Bütikofer) 表示。 “他们很清楚，普京对乌克兰的威胁的意义远远超出了乌克兰本身。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="402" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817981?width=700&amp;height=402" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">拜登总统和英国领导人苏纳克在北约峰会上向乌克兰总统泽伦斯基表示赞赏。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：道格·米尔斯/新闻池</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>华盛顿与其欧洲盟友之间的分歧在一系列问题上日益明显，从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-nato-summit-membership-fb0d863a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰最终加入北大西洋公约组织的前景</a>，到基辅<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">当前旨在收复被占领土的进攻</a>所需的军事能力，到短期内与克里姆林宫的任何和平解决方案。</p><p> “拜登的口号是， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amid-ukraine-war-and-internal-spats-nato-seeks-show-of-unity-cf9a0ad2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">联盟的团结</a>是重中之重，”为波兰政府提供咨询的华沙智库波兰国际事务研究所所长斯拉沃米尔·登布斯基 (Slawomir Dębski) 说。 “现在的问题是，是拜登政府落后于欧洲，是拜登政府在给团结制造麻烦。”</p><p>华盛顿仍然是乌克兰最大的支持者，拜登总统在维尔纽斯重申，美国的承诺不会动摇——警告普京正在做出“糟糕的赌注”，因为他怀疑西方的持久力和团结。</p><p>然而，大西洋两岸的政治风向却相反。美国共和党中相当多且不断增长的少数派希望结束对乌克兰的任何支持，而美国在战争中的角色很可能成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-2024-election-is-a-fight-over-americas-way-of-life-36d09b18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">明年总统选举</a>的一个问题。周四，一项禁止向乌克兰提供所有安全援助的提案获得了 70 名共和党人的支持，占众议院共和党议员总数的近三分之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3DACF2B9-57D8-4E08-9516-4CB823B825C5&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchanging-places-europeans-grow-more-assertive-on-ukraine-as-washington-shows-caution-e4b83acf&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北约领导人周三结束了在立陶宛举行的为期两天的会议，重申了对乌克兰的政治承诺，但未能就乌克兰加入该联盟的时间表达成一致。照片：卢多维奇·马林/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>，</p>寻求明年重返白宫的特朗普指责拜登冒着第三次世界大战的风险向乌克兰提供<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">集束弹药</a>（俄罗斯一直在大量使用这种弹药），并吹嘘他可以<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/watch-trump-says-as-president-hed-settle-ukraine-war-within-24-hours/0BCA9F18-D3BF-43DA-9220-C13587EAEDF2.html?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在24小时内</a>结束冲突，不用说如何。<p></p><p>短期内很少有欧洲主要领导人有类似的选举担忧。欧洲经济体已成功<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-moves-toward-cutting-a-last-source-of-russian-energy-2caf3859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">摆脱</a>对俄罗斯能源的依赖，即使是曾经支持普京的民族主义政党如今也很少公开支持莫斯科。去年推动基辅和莫斯科谈判的许多欧洲主要领导人，其中最重要的是法国总统马克龙，越来越多地认为，除非普京在战场上溃败或下台，否则无法就乌克兰问题达成任何协议。</p><p>卡米尔表示：“欧洲越来越相信，俄罗斯的失败需要非常明确，而至少在美国体系的某些角落，人们可能会认为，这需要是一场能够产生谈判结果的失败。”格兰德是布鲁塞尔欧洲外交关系委员会的政策研究员，直到去年一直担任北约助理秘书长。 “有这个细微差别。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817979?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">法国总统马克龙五月呼吁“由侵略受害者选择”的和平。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马丁·迪维塞克/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>拜登上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-visit-cements-finlands-pivot-away-from-neutrality-3fd65237?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在赫尔辛基发表讲话</a>时表示，他的希望和期望是“乌克兰在攻势上取得重大进展，并最终通过谈判达成解决方案。”乌克兰总统弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基</p>乌克兰一再表示，在乌克兰收复占该国领土约20%的被占土地并获得莫斯科赔偿之前，不可能达成任何解决方案。<p></p><p>在维尔纽斯峰会上，拜登政府拒绝就乌克兰问题进行谈判，称北约“在盟友同意且条件满足的情况下，将能够向乌克兰发出加入联盟的邀请”，令许多盟友感到惊讶。</p><p>泽连斯基抵达维尔纽斯后感到沮丧，他发表了一条激烈的推文。 “在与俄罗斯的谈判中，留下了一个机会来讨价还价乌克兰在北约的成员资格，”他写道。 “对于俄罗斯来说，这意味着继续实施恐怖活动的动力。”</p><p>乌克兰反腐败活动家和公民社会活动家达里亚·卡莱纽克(Daria Kaleniuk)在与美国国家安全顾问杰克·沙利文(Jake Sullivan)的尖锐交流中提出了这一点。她在维尔纽斯举行的北约公共论坛上问沙利文，拜登“没有邀请乌克兰加入北约，是因为他害怕俄罗斯，害怕俄罗斯失败，害怕乌克兰获胜吗？”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>她推测华盛顿和莫斯科之间存在秘密沟通，并补充道：“我应该让我的儿子在七年后满 18 岁的时候成为一名士兵并与俄罗斯人作战吗？”观众报以雷鸣般的掌声。</p><p>沙利文回应称，任何有关华盛顿将以乌克兰为代价与克里姆林宫谈判达成秘密协议的说法“完全没有根据、毫无道理”。</p><p>他说：“有很多阴谋论根本不基于任何现实。”他补充说，“美国人民确实应该得到一定程度的感激。”美国官员向欧洲对话者发出了类似的信息，否认与莫斯科有任何秘密交易，其中一些人表示，他们仍然不相信这些否认，并担心美国对乌克兰的政策越来越受到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-ukraine-stance-worries-europe-d999df46?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国政治日程</a>的限制。</p><p>沙利文周日在美国全国广播公司 (NBC) 节目中重申，乌克兰加入北约“无需与包括俄罗斯在内的任何国家进行谈判”。</p><p>对乌克兰军事援助动态的变化加剧了华盛顿与许多欧洲盟友之间的紧张关系。尽管欧洲和美国对乌克兰的总体援助大致相同，但华盛顿仍然向基辅提供大部分武器。然而，近几个月来，在提供基辅称其军事成功所需的新型、更先进、射程更远的装备方面，拜登政府已被欧洲国家超越。</p><p>虽然美国尚未同意提供基辅寻求的 ATACMS 导弹，但伦敦和巴黎已经提供了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-deadly-new-missile-was-created-to-hit-saddam-hussein-in-his-bathtub-75e04412?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">远程巡航导弹</a>，可以打击乌克兰被占领地区的任何地方，并用于攻击俄罗斯指挥所、后勤节点和弹药库。华盛顿尚未交付<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-begin-training-ukrainian-forces-on-abrams-tanks-in-may-a0dbdae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">承诺的艾布拉姆斯坦克</a>，而数十辆德国和英国坦克已经投入战场。拜登政府还放慢了欧洲向基辅提供荷兰、丹麦和挪威等国拥有的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-missiles-stretch-ukraines-air-defenses-14ad9454?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">F-16 飞机的</a>努力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817978?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲比美国更快地向乌克兰提供坦克，例如翻新的德国豹式坦克。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Morris Macmatzen / Pool/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “我们过去认为问题出在德国，但现在越来越明显，问题出在华盛顿，”前立陶宛外交部长、前欧盟驻莫斯科大使维高达斯·乌萨卡斯 (Vygaudas Ušackas) 表示。</p><p>在欧洲内部，最重大的转变也许发生在欧盟唯一的核国家法国。去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/film-reveals-macrons-futile-diplomacy-with-putin-before-ukraine-war-11656695036?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">寻求与普京进行外交接触的</a>马克龙越来越相信乌克兰需要取得胜利——他在 5 月 31 日在斯洛伐克布拉迪斯拉发发表的具有里程碑意义的演讲中表达了这一信念。尊重国际法，是由侵略受害者乌克兰人民选择的。”</p><p>波兰智库负责人登布斯基表示：“法国确实有战略文化、战略眼光，能够着眼长远，这就是为什么他们现在离北欧国家和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/natos-front-line-countries-are-doubling-down-on-defense-spending-others-arent-733a3ef1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">北约东翼</a>更近了——这些国家别无选择，只能考虑长远、长期后果。”</p><p>在美国，反对帮助乌克兰的社会保守派、民族主义或本土主义政治思潮在欧洲往往有着截然不同的态度。意大利就是一个典型的例子。总理乔治亚·梅洛尼（Giorgia Meloni）的右翼联盟包括历史上对普京友好的政党，自去年十月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/giorgia-meloni-taking-power-in-italy-promises-a-pro-western-course-11666431846?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上台</a>以来，他已成为基辅最直言不讳的捍卫者之一。</p><p>罗马国际事务研究所所长纳塔莉·托奇表示，“即使在一些国家向右倾斜的欧洲，这也并不一定意味着放弃对乌克兰的支持。” “像梅洛尼这样的民族主义者会对乌克兰正在进行民族解放战争这一事实感到强烈。”</p><p>欧洲与乌克兰的距离很近，而美国的距离很远，这解释了不同的态度，她补充道：“归根结底，地理因素很重要。美国距离很远，可以接受妥协，而欧洲人则更难以接受。”</p><p>写信给雅罗斯拉夫·特罗菲莫夫 (yaroslav Trofimov)： <a href="mailto:yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 15:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/having-places-europeans-grow-more-assertive-on-ukraine-as-washington-shows-caution-e4b83acf</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/having-places-europeans-grow-more-assertive-on-ukraine-as-washington-shows-caution-e4b83acf<author><![CDATA[Yaroslav Trofimov]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[High-Earning Retirement Savers Are Losing Some of Their 401(k) Tax Break]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>对于年收入超过 145,000 美元的人，必须在税后进行补缴供款<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816650/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 ELENA SCOTTI/华尔街日报拍摄，ISTOCK (3)，PIXELSQUID<span>照片插图由 ELENA SCOTTI/华尔街日报拍摄，ISTOCK (3)，PIXELSQUID</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001052376"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001052376"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 10:47（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-breaks-401k-contributions-2868ffdc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>从明年开始，数百万高收入美国人预计将失去受欢迎的减税政策。</p><p> 50 岁及以上的储户每年可以在其 401(k) 账户中进行补缴，符合条件的工人今年可以在账户中额外存入 7,500 美元，总计 30,000 美元。</p><p>从明年开始，这些补足资金将仅存入那些上一年收入超过 145,000 美元的人的税后 Roth 账户。这一变化是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/401k-changes-retirement-plans-congress-11671482120?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国会去年 12 月通过的</a>一系列新规则的一部分。据先锋集团 (Vanguard Group) 称，到 2022 年，16% 的合格参与者利用了追赶优势。</p><p>这一变化意味着许多工人将在高收入年份预先为其补足的资金缴税，而不是在退休时缴纳较低税级的税款。它将重塑有多少美国人为退休储蓄并制定财务和遗产规划策略。</p><p>用税前资金进行补缴对高收入者来说是一个福音。例如，35% 范围内的人如果补缴 7,500 美元，将获得 2,625 美元的税收减免，而 22% 范围内的人将扣除 1,650 美元。</p><p>虽然根据新规定，一些美国人将缴纳更多税款，但财务顾问表示，让接近退休的人将更多资金投入罗斯基金会有好处，因为罗斯基金的资金会增长，而且可以免税提取。这些变化不适用于 IRA，它允许 50 岁及以上的储户在 2023 年在 6,500 美元的年度限额之上追加缴纳 1,000 美元。</p><p>纽约布鲁克林的财务顾问克里斯蒂娜·古列梅蒂 (Cristina Guglielmetti) 表示：“罗斯是一个非常强大的储蓄工具，我会尽力为所有客户至少存入一些美元，无论税级如何。”</p><h3>罗斯的好处</h3><p>传统账户中有存款的退休人员在提取资金时必须缴纳普通所得税。在罗斯账户中，工人们可以积累一大笔免税资金，供多年来使用，在这些年里，利用其他账户将把他们推入更高的税级或迫使他们支付更高的医疗保险费。</p><p>埃德·斯洛特说，许多人认为他们在退休时将处于较低的税率，但情况并非总是如此，</p>专门研究退休账户的顾问。<p></p><p>由于高收入者经常在传统的 401(k) 和个人退休账户中积累大量余额，因此当国税局要求他们在 73 岁时开始从这些账户中提取资金时，许多人发现自己处于相同或更高的税级。</p><p>他表示，追赶缴款的新要求是“送给高收入者的礼物”，否则他们可能会忽视免税增长的好处。</p><p>顾问表示，由于罗斯账户是免税的，因此对于大储户来说，它们是比应税经纪账户更好的选择，后者要求所有者每年就股息、利息和已实现的资本利得纳税。罗斯家族对于继承人也有很大的优势，他们可以获得免税收入。</p><p>大多数非配偶受益人必须<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/irs-changes-guidelines-for-inherited-iras-causing-confusion-and-pushback-11659309278?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 10 年内清算</a>罗斯账户和传统账户。</p><h3>公司呼吁推迟</h3><p>尽管这一变化将于 1 月 1 日开始实施，但一些公司和计划提供商表示，他们需要更多时间来应对后勤挑战，确定谁上一年的收入超过 145,000 美元，并重新调整工资单和其他系统，以确保他们的赶上变成了罗斯。</p><p>超过 200 家雇主、401(k) 记录保存者和薪资提供者最近致函国会，要求推迟两年。这封信由达美航空、安海斯布希公司和富达投资公司等公司签署，该公司为雇主管理着 24,800 个企业退休账户，信中表示，许多公司将无法在最后期限前及时更改其系统。</p><p>信中称：“对于其中许多计划，除非这一要求被推迟……他们唯一的合规手段将是取消 2024 年的所有补缴捐款。”</p><p>莎朗·卢卡奇,</p>纽约州递延薪酬委员会执行董事表示，该州310亿美元的递延薪酬计划允许使用该计划的2,236名当地雇主决定是否提供罗斯。目前，有 1,200 人选择不这样做，在某些情况下是因为他们的工资系统无法处理罗斯的捐款。<p></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Roth 对于 401(k) 追赶捐款有意义吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>她说，到目前为止，1,200 人中有 150 人同意在 1 月 1 日之前添加罗斯。</p><p>目前，Fidelity 的 24,800 名 401(k) 客户中有 30% 缺乏 Roth 功能，这家总部位于波士顿的公司工作场所退休产品和平台主管戴夫·格雷 (Dave Gray) 表示。格雷说，除非这些雇主在新法律生效之前采用罗斯选项，否则他们将不得不取消所有工人的补缴缴款。</p><p>薪资提供者、雇主和 401(k) 记录保存者正在努力满足最后期限，但正在等待监管机构就一些问题提供指导，包括他们是否必须寻求高收入者的许可才能将追赶捐款存入 Roth 或可以这样做格雷说，就这么自然而然地。他说，如果指导意见在今年晚些时候发布，公司可能没有足够的时间来调整其系统。</p><p>拥有 250 名会员的全国政府固定缴款管理员协会执行董事马修·彼得森 (Matthew Petersen) 表示，一些退休储蓄计划，包括南达科他州和爱达荷州政府雇员的退休储蓄计划，除非州立法机构通过法律，否则不能添加罗斯。他说，一些雇主必须与工会谈判才能增加罗斯。</p><p>美国财政部发言人表示，计划在不久的将来发布指导意见，但拒绝就推迟的请求发表评论。</p><h3>国会的修复</h3><p>另一个悬而未决的问题是国会去年年底通过的退休法案中的一个起草错误，许多专门从事退休计划的律师将其解释为禁止从 2024 年开始为所有工人进行补缴。</p><p>在 5 月 23 日致财政部和国税局的信中，参议员迈克·克拉波（爱达荷州共和党）和众议员理查德·尼尔（马萨诸塞州民主党）等议员表示，国会打算“引入技术纠正立法”来解决这一问题。</p><p>信中说：“国会无意禁止追加捐款。”</p><p>写信给安妮·特尔格森： <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2d22c5e9-a490-4c14-9b85-792395763a6e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 14:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-breaks-401k-contributions-2868ffdc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-breaks-401k-contributions-2868ffdc<author><![CDATA[Anne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>税务策略</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>税务策略</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The New Workday Dead Zone When Nothing Gets Done]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>下午晚些时候，很多同事都消失了，这就是为什么这么多经理讨厌混合工作的原因<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816492/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Blake Cale 为《华尔街日报》提供，iStock (2)<span>照片插图由 Blake Cale 为《华尔街日报》提供，iStock (2)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001051789"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001051789"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-498821" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers" itemprop="url" rel="author">卡勒姆·博彻斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>下午 4 点的会议被取消，因为一半的团队成员无法参加。您发送一封电子邮件，其中包含主要讨论点，回复从晚上一直持续到第二天早上。本来可以在晚餐前达成的共识现在却在第二天形成。</p><p>传统的下班时间已经成为许多公司的死区，但员工们并不仅仅是为了放松一下一天的工作。工人们表示，他们利用下午 4 点至 6 点的弹性工作时间轮流带孩子拼车、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-working-out-during-the-workday-is-the-ultimate-power-move-11672863482?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去健身房</a>或避开交通拥堵，通常需要在晚上第三班才能完成当天的任务。当领导者认为他们没有投入八个小时或更多小时的工作时，他们会感到不满，并且不愿意放弃制定自己时间表的自由。</p><p>尽管磨牙的通勤和昂贵的午餐又回来了，但许多员工仍然坚持着新冠病毒时代早下班、晚补班的习惯。斯坦福大学的一项<a href="https://nbloom.people.stanford.edu/sites/g/files/sbiybj24291/files/media/file/golfingfromhome.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">研究</a>表明，工作日下午 4 点，高尔夫球场就挤满了人，纽约市的许多餐馆也是如此。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>研究人员记录了他们所谓的“<a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/worklab/triple-peak-day" target="_blank" class="icon none">三重高峰</a>”现象，即员工的键盘活动在早上和下午激增，然后在晚上 10 点左右出现第三次。科技巨头预测这种模式将持续下去。</p><p>在最近的一个月 Microsoft Teams 软件使用情况样本中，安排在下午 4 点至 6 点之间进行的虚拟会议和面对面会议的比例较去年同期下降了 7%，尽管办公室返工现象普遍存在。</p><p>老板可以把员工拖回办公桌前，但如果你能把他们留在那里直到朝九晚五的工作日结束或更长时间，那就祝你好运了。下午 4 点至 6 点的死区是许多高管对混合工作感到暴躁的原因之一。他们说，这是联系人员最困难的时期，如果每个人都在场并亲自负责，事情会更容易，尽管许多员工似乎也提前离开办公室。</p><p><strong>灵活性的代价</strong></p><p>可替代的时间对于那些进行可替代的人来说非常有用。对于经理和同事来说，一个人的休息可能会让另一个人头疼。</p><p> Kanarys 产品营销副总裁 Albert Fong 表示：“许多公司都采取了宽松的做法，认为我们都是成年人，因此每个人都会自律并在工作的任何时间都保持积极性。” ，多元化培训软件制造商。 “那不是真的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="622" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816891?width=639&amp;height=622" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Kanarys 产品营销副总裁 Albert Fong 表示，灵活性可能是一个陷阱，会助长我们永远在线的工作文化。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：方伟强</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Fong 补充道，灵活性可能是一个陷阱，会助长我们永远在线的工作文化。他经常发现自己整个晚上都在刷新手机收件箱，或者在周日打开笔记本电脑，以查看随时工作的同事发来的消息，而不是在下午晚些时候的聚会中精力充沛地完成一天的工作。</p><p>微软未来工作计划总经理 Colette Stallbaumer 总结道：“我们如何才能让我的灵活性不再成为你的挑战？”</p><p>麦肯锡公司副合伙人安娜·保拉·卡尔沃 (Ana Paula Calvo) 表示，她考虑改变自己的工作时间会对他人产生怎样的影响。她有时会在晚上或周末工作，以弥补许多工作日下午 5:30 去托儿所的时间。在任何新项目开始时，她都会召开规范制定会议，让她的团队知道他们没有工作压力小时。</p><p> “人们知道，如果我在晚上 11 点回复他们，并不意味着我希望他们立即回复，”她说。</p><p><strong>它可以等待——或者也许不能</strong></p><p>几位企业领导人告诉我，为了招募和留住顶尖人才，有必要满足员工的个人约会——欢乐时光瑜伽、青少年大号课程。他们补充说，不过，这肯定会让会议达到法定人数变得困难。其他人，尤其是没有孩子的工人，则抱怨说，自从人们普遍接受在正常工作时间休息以来，他们的工作日变得更长且更难以预测。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>下午 4 点至 6 点，您和您的同事在做什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>俄勒冈州的制药运营总监玛丽亚·巴纳赫 (Maria Banach) 表示，有时她想召集小组来解决问题，结果却发现团队中有人已经离线了几个小时。这看起来似乎不是很长，但她的同事分布在多个时区，重叠的工作时间也很有限。巴纳赫说，如果一两个人提早离开，问题可能会持续一夜，但每一天都很宝贵。她公司生产的药品在生产后17天就过期了。</p><p> “安排会议变得很困难，但我学会了：在早上进行，而不是在周五，”她说。</p><p>一些高管已经接受、甚至欣然接受这样一个现实：下午 4 点到 6 点之间几乎没有什么事情可做。 安东尼·斯蒂芬 (Anthony Stephan)</p>德勤美国首席学习官表示，录制的教程现在已成为该公司专业发展计划的核心内容。他说，让员工聚集在一起参加一天结束时的培训课程已经不再是一种选择。当他们愿意时，他们会磨练新技能。<p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="852" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815827?width=639&amp;height=852" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Komet USA 首席执行官 Mercedes Aycinena 通常在下午 5 点离开办公室与孩子们共度时光，然后在需要时再继续工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：梅赛德斯·艾辛纳</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>斯蒂芬是五个孩子的父亲，他在下午 5 点强迫自己停下来。他最初担心其他人会在他下班后继续忙碌，但现在他意识到其他人正在提前或准时结束。对于紧急情况，他告诉他的团队在电子邮件主题行中添加#riticnow。他认为，大多数事情都可以等到第二天早上 5 点 15 分锻炼之后再做。</p><p>在位于南卡罗来纳州的牙科设备制造商 Komet USA，下午 4 点之后或周五下午开会违反公司政策，特殊情况除外。去年晋升为最高职位的首席执行官梅赛德斯·艾辛纳(Mercedes Aycinena)在对员工进行民意调查后于去年秋天介绍了这些日历块。</p><p> Aycinena 拥有约 100 名员工，她通常在下午 5 点离开办公室，与她的三个孩子共度时光，然后根据需要稍后再继续工作。她还允许下属调整工作时间，并认为灵活性有助于将过去一年的人员流动率从 50% 降低到 15%。</p><p> “我讨厌四点之后的会议，”她说。 “我的大脑已经完成了。”</p><p>写信给Callum Borchers： <a href="mailto:callum.borchers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">callum.borchers@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/12865c40-068f-4100-aa18-f73fd5f66fae.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0<author><![CDATA[Callum Borchers]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How Allbirds Lost Its Way]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>质量投诉和棘手的漏洞一直困扰着这家热鞋公司，该公司推出了一系列新产品，但发现环境可持续性很难推销<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817376/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Allbirds co-founders Joey Zwillinger and Tim Brown at Allbirds headquarters in San Francisco last week." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Allbirds co-founders Joey Zwillinger and Tim Brown at Allbirds headquarters in San Francisco last week. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001053252"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001053252"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/suzanne-kapner" itemprop="url" rel="author">Suzanne Kapner</a></span> | Photographs by Carolyn Fong for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 16, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-allbirds-lost-its-way-a44d5415"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BIRD" class="company-name">Allbirds</a> shot to fame with eco-friendly wool sneakers worn by Silicon Valley tech bros, Barack Obama and seemingly everyone else. In 2021, employees gathered in its San Francisco headquarters to see its next big product: wool leggings.</p><p> When a model tried them on, employees noticed they were see-through. “I can see your underwear,” one exclaimed. By then, Allbirds had already ordered tens of thousands of pairs—many of which were unsellable, according to people familiar with the situation.</p><p> The rollout of the leggings, which were discontinued a year later, was just one in a series of missteps by the startup that was once a cultural symbol of cool and is now a standout example of a hot company that lost its way.</p><p> Allbirds is cutting back as its revenue shrinks and its cash pile dwindles. Its shares have lost more than 95% of their value since a November 2021 initial public offering and on Friday closed at $1.28.</p><p> The company, founded in 2016, tapped into the idea that businesses can make money, be innovative and do good in the world, especially when it comes to the environment. To help the planet, co-founders Joey Zwillinger and Tim Brown believed consumers didn&#39;t have to stop buying stuff, just that the stuff needed to be made differently. It leaned on its popularity to pursue a hyperfast growth model pioneered by other online disrupters such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WRBY" class="company-name">Warby Parker</a> that sold goods directly to consumers.</p><p> It turns out that not everyone wants to dress head-to-toe in merino wool, which <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/allbirds-to-sell-wool-and-tree-based-workout-clothes-taking-on-nike-and-lululemon-11629192602?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">although better for the environment</a> than nylon or polyester, isn&#39;t as durable. Customers complained of holes in their sneakers months after buying them. And the leggings, which were made from a blend of wool and other fibers, in addition to being see-through, didn&#39;t hold their shape, the people said. Allbirds said the sheerness was limited to one light color and that it was a minor issue caught at an early stage.</p><p> After the initial success of its original shoe, the Wool Runner, Allbirds tried to expand beyond its base of 30- and 40-year-olds to attract younger customers with more technical running shoes and other sneakers in brighter colors and edgier patterns. It also pushed into new categories—underwear, puffer jackets and golf shoes—but struggled to replicate the success of its first shoe.</p><p> The company lost focus, unsure if it was selling to sneakerheads or soccer moms, said the people, who are familiar with Allbirds&#39; product development and marketing. A key business assumption, that consumers&#39; concerns about the environment would drive them to buy sustainable products, has been a tough sell.</p><p> Some of Allbirds&#39; loyal customers, including the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/allbirds-were-the-tech-bro-it-shoe-then-the-tech-bros-moved-on-11671858003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Silicon Valley crowd</a> , have dropped the brand. Its stumbles have opened the door to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/on-running-sneakers-cloudmonster-11648642860?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">other sneakers that are supplanting</a> Allbirds among <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hoka-shoes-running-deckers-ugly-sneakers-832ba4fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tech and fashion trendsetters</a> , such as On and Hoka. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817415?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An Allbirds retail store in San Francisco.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For Zwillinger and Brown, who were millionaires many times over on paper when Allbirds went public but didn&#39;t sell stock in the offering, it&#39;s been a humbling experience.</p><p> Zwillinger has a saying: Customers will accept one degree of weirdness, but not two. Iterations of existing styles are preferred over brands pushing too far into new categories. He said in an interview that shoppers who came to Allbirds for its original shoes weren&#39;t ready to buy technical gear such as running shoes or workout clothes from the brand. He acknowledged problems with the leggings and other workout clothes. “You&#39;ve got to get [the] fit right,” he said.</p><p> Brown, in a separate interview, added: “As we&#39;ve tried to expand and grow the brand, we created products that haven&#39;t quite met the mark.”</p><h3> Products for &#39;Charlie&#39;</h3><p> Until recently, Zwillinger and Brown, who are both 42 years old, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/allbirds-dual-ceo-arrangement-is-a-rare-specimen-11601652381?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">served as co-CEOs</a> , working at desks across from each other in an office with an open floor plan. It&#39;s a model that has worked well at Warby Parker. Neil Blumenthal, Warby&#39;s co-founder and co-CEO, is a friend of Zwillinger&#39;s from business school and sits on Allbirds&#39; board. But it has produced <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/co-ceos-are-out-of-style-why-is-netflix-resurrecting-the-management-model-11594987416?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mixed results at other companies</a> , including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CRM" class="">Salesforce</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ORCL" class="company-name">Oracle</a></p> and German software giant SAP, which have all moved away from the structure.<p></p><p> “It&#39;s either the best thing or the worst thing,” Brown said. “There is no in between.”</p><p> In May, Allbirds abandoned its joint stewardship and named Zwillinger sole CEO. Brown now oversees partnerships, brand awareness and culture as its chief innovation officer.</p><p> The Allbirds co-founders said the double-CEO model initially worked because they had complementary skills. Zwillinger, an industrial engineer with a Wharton MBA and a salt-and-pepper beard, oversaw finance, operations and technology. Brown, who played professional soccer, studied graphic design in college and earned an MBA, focused on product design, branding and marketing.</p><p> As the business floundered, disagreements arose, the people familiar said. Employees would sit through a meeting with Brown, who would talk about targeting younger shoppers—known internally as “Charlie”—with edgier designs and technical gear such as running shoes. Then, they would go into a meeting with Zwillinger, who would say the prime customer is a 45-year-old who buys the shoes because they are comfortable, the people said.</p><p> Brown and Zwillinger said they never disagreed on strategy. “Every decision that we made, we made together,” Brown said. An Allbirds spokesman said “Charlie” was meant to signify a broad age group, from 25- to 40-year-olds, not just younger shoppers.</p><p> Also in May, the company said it was laying off 9% of its US corporate staff, its second round of job cuts in less than a year. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/272820f4-aee7-46d7-bac1-a7cdc3792ba2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> Environmental concerns</h3><p> In 2008, Brown started thinking about creating a different type of sneaker—one that wasn&#39;t covered in logos or made from synthetic materials—when he was playing professional soccer in New Zealand, where he grew up. The idea crystallized during an entrepreneurship class he took in 2013 at Northwestern University&#39;s Kellogg School of Management, during a semester he studied there while earning his master&#39;s degree from the London School of Economics.</p><p> Carter Cast, a former <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PEP" class="company-name">PepsiCo</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WMT" class="company-name">Walmart</a> executive who taught the class, tried to talk him out of it. “I told him shoes are a competitive category,” Cast said. Nevertheless, Cast was so impressed with the prototype Brown created, with the help of a research grant from the New Zealand Wool Association, that he urged him to put his idea on the crowdfunding platform Kickstarter. Brown raised $120,000 in five days.</p><p> Brown and Zwillinger met through their wives, who were Dartmouth College roommates. Zwillinger had been developing renewable energy sources at a San Francisco biotech company. Brown, who was then living in London, flew to the Bay Area to meet with Zwillinger and get his advice on what to do after the success of the Kickstarter campaign. They decided to team up.</p><p> “I wondered if there was an opportunity to help create a brand that could change the way people thought about consumption,” Zwillinger said.</p><p> Allbirds took off as environmental concerns were reaching a fever pitch with wildfires burning out of control in California, hurricanes leveling parts of Florida and scientists warning that time is running out to reverse the effects of global warming. Brown and Zwillinger said they named the company Allbirds because when New Zealand was first settled by humans its wildlife consisted mainly of birds, not mammals.</p><p> Their first shoe quickly amassed a devoted following for its comfort and eco-friendly materials. The Wool Runner&#39;s upper is made from merino wool, the midsole from a foam produced from sugar cane and the laces from recycled plastic bottles. At first Allbirds sold its goods only online. It opened its first bricks-and-mortar store in 2017. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/aec3e0e1-0e0b-400b-93f8-1d698d6da1b3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In an early partnership, Allbirds set up shop inside the original <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SHAK" class="company-name">Shake Shack</a> in New York City for one day in 2018 and sold limited-edition sneakers. People lined up around the block for the shoes, prompting some Allbirds employees to compare the company&#39;s gravitational pull to that of Supreme, the ultracool streetwear brand.</p><p> The company offered to share its environmental innovations with competitors, even as it accused some of them in lawsuits of knocking off its designs.</p><p> By the time Allbirds went public in November 2021, it had a market value of $4 billion. For the full year of 2021, it reported a loss of $45.4 million on $277.5 million in sales.</p><h3> Fast expansion</h3><p> Allbirds launched its second sneaker in 2020, the Tree Dasher, made of eucalyptus tree fiber. It marketed it as an entry-level running shoe, pitting it against industry giants <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NKE" class="">Nike</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Adidas and others. It pushed further into the running business two years later with the Tree Flyer.</p><p> Sales of the Flyer were disappointing, according to the company. Some customers said it lacked the support and cushioning needed for hard-core running. It was also more expensive, priced at $160, compared with $95 for the Wool Runner when it launched.</p><p> “Consumers weren&#39;t ready to shell out $160 for a technical running performance product from us, given that&#39;s not the ethos [of our] DNA,” Zwillinger told analysts in March. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1146" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/fd2a49fa-f749-4af3-93bb-b93792c734ff-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Allbirds ran into problems with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/allbirds-to-sell-wool-and-tree-based-workout-clothes-taking-on-nike-and-lululemon-11629192602?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a line of workout clothes</a> made from merino wool. Allbirds says wool is naturally suited for exercise, because it absorbs moisture and regulates temperature. That wasn&#39;t always the experience of customers.</p><p> Edward Yruma, a senior research analyst at Piper Sandler who follows Allbirds, took a photograph of himself last year after a run in one of the T-shirts and sent it to company executives. “It was so wet it looked like I had taken a shower with the shirt on,” Yruma said.</p><p> The Pacer, a sneaker made of vegan leather that was introduced in 2022, didn&#39;t live up to expectations. Other types of apparel that Allbirds introduced such as $250 puffer jackets and $88 dresses, also made from merino wool, didn&#39;t attract customers and had to be discounted. The company has since discontinued its leggings and other performance clothing and liquidated unsold apparel at a cost of roughly $13 million.</p><p> One big problem: holes. Sarah Mattina was on her third pair of Allbirds&#39; Tree Dasher style, which she got as a Christmas gift in December. By April, both big toes were peeking out. Her two previous pairs lasted a bit longer—about a year—before they also developed holes. The 28-year-old San Francisco resident said she is done with the brand.</p><p> “My next sneakers won&#39;t be Allbirds,” said Mattina, the marketing director for a nonprofit. “I&#39;ll probably buy Hoka or On, those are the new hot shoes.”</p><p> Allbirds said it has made more than 30 changes to try to prevent holes from forming in its shoes, including tightening the weave and adjusting the mold on which the shoes are made.</p><p> Brown said novel materials have a learning curve. Zwillinger said competitors&#39; shoes also develop holes.</p><h3> Joining with designers</h3><p> To expand its customer base, Allbirds went after younger shoppers by partnering with designers like Rosie Assoulin, who created a limited-edition collection of slide sandals for the brand. It also teamed with the Portuguese graphic artist and illustrator Bráulio Amado to produce Tree Dasher sneakers in colorful prints.</p><p> The effort failed to attract enough younger customers, partly because many of the company&#39;s products, such as its colorful ballet flats, tended to skew older. As one insider put it, Allbirds wasn&#39;t going to convince kids in downtown Oakland, Calif., to ditch their Air Jordans when it was selling ballet flats.</p><p> The Allbirds spokesman said Oakland teens were never the company&#39;s target and the partnerships weren&#39;t designed for younger customers, but rather to expand its base among core consumers. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a3684e23-0515-468f-a73c-0dbbb32ad3d5.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> As Allbirds lost its footing, it enlisted the help of the Boston Consulting Group to conduct a study of thousands of consumers. The conclusion: It must go back to its roots. Zwillinger unveiled the new strategy to analysts in March telling them that as the company tilted younger, it lost focus on its core.</p><p> Gone are the dresses and puffers. Allbirds is dropping much of its apparel, except for underwear, socks, T-shirts and sweats that proved more popular with its customers. It is also doubling down on bestselling products such as the Wool Runner and Tree Dasher, which it plans to update with new colors and styles. In June, it introduced the M0.0nshot, a sock-like sneaker that it says sucks more carbon from the atmosphere than the process of creating it emits.</p><p> The company is also slowing the pace of store openings and weighing whether to sell goods internationally through third-party distributors, which is less costly than operating its own stores in those markets. It currently has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/warby-parker-allbirds-everlane-parachute-collars-co-stores-e4b94623?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">about 59 stores</a> across nine countries, with 42 locations in the US</p><p> Analysts expect the company to post its first annual sales decline as a public company this year. In 2022, it reported a loss of $101.4 million on $297.8 million in revenue.</p><h3> Business and sustainability</h3><p> Allbirds said it isn&#39;t changing its commitment to sustainability, even though it doesn&#39;t always drive shoppers to buy its products. Emails sent to customers touting the environmental benefits of Allbirds shoes and clothing produced fewer sales than messages that prioritized comfort among other attributes.</p><p> Environmental concerns are among the least important attributes consumers look for when buying shoes and clothing, according to a survey in March of 750 US consumers by Wedbush Securities. Comfort and price are among the most important.</p><p> “It&#39;s admirable that they want to be environmentally friendly,” said Wedbush analyst Tom Nikic. “However, it doesn&#39;t resonate with consumers.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817382?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Shoeboxes at an Allbirds retail store in San Francisco.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Brown suggested that Allbirds is ahead of its time. “When you look back to when people were smoking on airplanes, that looks ridiculous now,” Brown said.</p><p> Zwillinger said people come to Allbirds for sustainability but end up purchasing because the products are comfortable, stylish and reasonably priced.</p><p> He said he knows from his own experience that people don&#39;t want to pay more for sustainable products. When he was working in biotech and his team tried to market new, eco-friendly materials, companies would at first say, “That sounds great,” he said. “Then it was like, &#39;You know what? We actually just want plastic, it&#39;s cheaper.&#39;”</p><p> Write to Suzanne Kapner at <a href="mailto:suzanne.kapner@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">suzanne.kapner@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-allbirds-lost-its-way-a44d5415</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-allbirds-lost-its-way-a44d5415<author><![CDATA[Suzanne Kapner]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>leder</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Footwear</category><category>零售批发</category><category>Shoe Retailing</category><category>专业零售</category><category>Clothing/Textiles</category><category>消费品</category><category>Leisure/Travel Goods</category><category>零售</category><category>Sports Footwear</category><category> Sports Goods</category><category> Sports Clothing/Footwear</category><category> New Products/Services</category><category> Management</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Corporate Governance</category><category> Corporate Social Responsibility</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境/社会/治理</category><category>Products/Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>可持续发展/可持续发展</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Allbirds</category><category> BIRD</category><category> new products</category><category> services</category><category> management</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>corporate governance</category><category> corporate social responsibility</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境的</category><category>社会的</category><category>治理</category><category>products</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>可持续发展</category><category>可持续性</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>鞋类</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>shoe retailing</category><category>专业零售</category><category>clothing</category><category> textiles</category><category>消费品</category><category>闲暇</category><category>travel goods</category><category> sports footwear</category><category> sports goods</category><category> sports clothing </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The No-Nonsense Georgia Prosecutor on a Collision Course With Donald Trump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> District attorney relishes complicated cases, while former president chides her probe as partisan <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816865/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="富尔顿县地方检察官法尼·威利斯说，她的父亲教会了她准备审判的重要性。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis says her father taught her the importance of preparing for trial. Brynn Anderson/Associated Press <span>Brynn Anderson/Associated Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056440"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056440"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cameron-mcwhirter" itemprop="url" rel="author">Cameron McWhirter</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jan-wolfe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jan Wolfe</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 16, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> ATLANTA—A Fulton County Board of Commissioners meeting in the summer of 2021 was proceeding like most mundane local government gatherings. Then Fani Willis came to the podium.</p><p> The county&#39;s then-newly elected district attorney&#39;s presentation was more like a closing argument of a trial than the traditional recitation of figures from a department head, as she demanded more funding for her office to handle a crime wave and case backlog.</p><p> “If there is anyone in here confused and thinks I&#39;m in here to talk about widgets, I&#39;m here to talk about human life,” she said.</p><p> Her office got more funding.</p><p> Willis has carved out a reputation in Georgia legal circles as a no-nonsense prosecutor and workaholic who relishes taking on complex cases. Her path to power <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-special-grand-jury-completes-donald-trump-investigation-11673283589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has put her on a collision course</a> with former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> , whose behavior after the 2020 election is thought to be central to her investigation of alleged attempts to overturn President Biden&#39;s narrow victory in this state. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816971?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> District Attorney Fani Willis took part in the selection of a special grand jury in Atlanta to look into efforts to overturn the results of the 2020 election.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ben Gray/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> State grand juries were being seated in Atlanta last week, setting the stage for jurors to hear evidence soon. The case could lead to criminal indictments for Trump and others who sought vigorously to negate his loss here. For about 2½ years, Willis has led an extensive probe into the matter, including questioning under oath of politicians and Trump supporters such as Rudolph Giuliani, once his lawyer, and South Carolina Sen. Lindsey Graham, a political confidant.</p><p> Trump has lashed out at Willis, 51 years old, last year labeling her a “young, ambitious, Radical Left Democrat &#39;Prosecutor&#39; from Georgia.” Trump and his supporters have repeatedly denied wrongdoing and attacked her investigation as partisan. Trump asked Georgia&#39;s highest court on Thursday <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-asks-georgias-highest-court-to-block-election-interference-investigation-5c14b0e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to effectively shut down</a> the criminal investigation.</p><p> In an interview, Willis declined to discuss specifics of the case, but said she was confident that what she brings to a grand jury will stick. She defends her office as fair.</p><p> “Our office has very few cases that are no-billed,” she said, meaning a grand jury has declined to indict. She added later, “I refuse to fail.”</p><p> Willis said she is at her desk by 6:30 am and stays until at least 7 pm She has asked staff to split shifts to keep up with her. The obsessive work ethic has hurt her family life, she said.</p><p> A longtime prosecutor, she once described herself as “one of the best murder prosecutors in this country.” Former co-workers said she is a stickler for preparation in cases and excellent in persuading juries.</p><p> “You look at her and she doesn&#39;t come across as the ice queen,” said Clint Rucker, a criminal-defense attorney who worked closely with Willis for years in the DA&#39;s office. “And then she opens her mouth, she roars. And it catches people off guard. I love to watch it.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816903?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Former President Donald Trump appeared in April in court in Manhattan.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Seth Wenig/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In April, Manhattan prosecutors <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indictment-new-york-7e64e016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">charged Trump with 34 counts</a> of falsifying business records relating to hush-money payments. In June, he was indicted in federal court in Florida on 37 counts that he <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-associate-also-indicted-in-mar-a-lago-documents-case-759cbb17?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">illegally retained and shared</a> classified national-security documents after leaving the White House.</p><p> Trump pleaded not guilty in both cases. Willis told The Wall Street Journal she hasn&#39;t been focused on the cases outside her own investigation.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>If former President Donald Trump is indicted in Georgia, how do you think the case will unfold?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> In Georgia, the probe by Willis&#39;s office has focused on efforts by Trump and his supporters to reverse his loss in the state in 2020, the first for a GOP presidential candidate since 1992. Trump lost by about 12,000 votes out of about five million cast. He and his supporters repeatedly alleged the vote was fraudulent, although two statewide recounts overseen by the Republican secretary of state showed Biden won. Court challenges by Trump and others failed.</p><p> Willis was born in 1971 near Los Angeles. Her father, John C. Floyd III, was a founder of a faction of the Black Panthers but later grew disillusioned by the movement&#39;s infighting, according to a piece he wrote in a Black Los Angeles newspaper the same year his daughter was born.</p><p> Floyd became a criminal-defense attorney, and the family moved to Washington. Willis&#39;s parents divorced and she stayed with her father in Washington, often sitting in a courtroom as he represented clients, many of them facing serious charges.</p><p> Willis attended Howard University and graduated from Emory University law school in 1996. She began practicing law as a plaintiffs&#39; attorney and working in the Atlanta city solicitor&#39;s office. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="415" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816906?width=700&amp;height=415" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fani Willis helped win convictions in an Atlanta schools cheating conspiracy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kent D. Johnson/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In the WSJ interview, she said her father taught her the importance of preparing for trial, and teachers at Howard University stressed to her that being a Black woman meant she needed to work twice as hard to prove herself.</p><p> “She is diligent about preparation so that when she does speak, she does so with authority,” said Gwen Keyes Fleming, a Washington lawyer and former district attorney in neighboring DeKalb County who considers herself a mentor to Willis.</p><p> Rucker first became aware of Willis when he was a young prosecutor. He said a judge called him and said Willis was talented and should come to the DA&#39;s office to handle more serious cases. She joined in 2001, hired by then-DA Paul Howard.</p><p> Willis quickly began specializing in serious, complex crimes and by her estimation has handled more than 100 murders.</p><p> Her biggest case while working for Howard involved helping lead the team that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/11-atlanta-educators-convicted-in-cheating-scandal-1427914234?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">won multiple convictions</a> in a notorious cheating scandal involving Atlanta Public Schools teachers and staff. Rucker, who worked with Willis on that case, said the high-profile nature of it brought a lot of negative publicity to Willis and Rucker, who also is Black. Angry parents, local groups and even churches attacked the DA&#39;s office for bringing cases against Black teachers and school staff.</p><p> “But she was absolutely dogged about representing those kids,” Rucker said.</p><p> Brian Ross, a plaintiffs&#39; attorney who worked as a prosecutor for years in the Fulton County DA&#39;s office, with Willis as his direct supervisor, recalled one case that was several weeks out and for which he hadn&#39;t yet prepared much. Willis asked him to come to the grand-jury room. He thought he was walking into a one-on-one meeting. He entered to find about 20 people waiting for him in a mock-trial format. Willis asked him to deliver his opening remarks in the coming case.</p><p> “She forced me to be better,” he said.</p><p> Willis, a divorced mother of two daughters, left the DA&#39;s office in 2018 to go into private practice but quickly decided to run for a local judgeship. She lost that race and then decided to run against her old boss, Howard, who was embroiled in investigations into alleged misuse of funds and other issues.</p><p> Howard, who didn&#39;t respond to requests seeking comment, had repeatedly denied wrongdoing.</p><p> Willis defeated her former boss, and she took office right as The Washington Post reported on a Jan. 2, 2021, recording of Trump calling Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urged-georgia-secretary-of-state-to-overturn-election-results-11609707084?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pressing him to “find” votes</a> to overturn Trump&#39;s loss. Willis immediately launched an investigation. The Journal later <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/recording-of-trump-phone-call-to-georgia-lead-investigator-reveals-new-details-11615411561?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">published audio</a> of a December 2020 call of Trump urging the chief investigator of the Georgia Secretary of State&#39;s office to look for fraud during an audit of mail-in ballots.</p><p> State judges granted Willis a special grand jury to compel potential witnesses to testify. The special grand jury lacked the authority to issue indictments, but it did issue a report, only portions of which have been made public. The report stated that some of the witnesses might have lied under oath. Willis is expected to use the report to seek criminal indictments from a traditional grand jury. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="394" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816872?width=700&amp;height=394" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fulton County Superior Court Judge Robert McBurney and District Attorney Fani Willis take part in the seating of a grand jury in Atlanta on Tuesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brynn Anderson/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> One of Willis&#39;s biggest challenges has been coping with a historic surge in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/atlantas-crime-wave-makes-some-residents-look-to-the-suburbs-11615467182?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">violent crime that hit Atlanta</a> , fueled as in other cities by Covid-19 turmoil, racial unrest and a resurgence of drug-gang wars. Her office has brought charges against alleged gang members and she has held news conferences announcing arrests. Violent crime has dropped during her tenure.</p><p> Willis at times opted to bring sweeping racketeering charges that unnecessarily complicate matters, said Andrew Fleischman, an Atlanta defense lawyer. “I believe that in a city that has pretty active crimes and lots of backlogs, you could simply not indict cases in super-complicated ways,” he said.</p><p> In the election probe, Willis <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eight-trump-electors-granted-immunity-in-georgia-investigation-f557d950?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reached immunity deals</a> in April with at least eight Republican Party activists who were part of a group in 2020 that falsely declared Trump the winner in the state. Willis also wrote a letter to the Fulton County sheriff stating she would announce “charging decisions” in the probe between July 11 and Sept. 1.</p><p> Willis said friends often give her turtle figurines, an animal she admires.</p><p> “They are methodical,” she said. “But they get to their destination.”</p><p> Write to Cameron McWhirter at <a href="mailto:Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com</a> and Jan Wolfe at <a href="mailto:jan.wolfe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jan.wolfe@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8<author><![CDATA[Cameron McWhirterJan Wolfe]]></author><category> wsj-usnews</category><category>专有的</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Regional Politics</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Andrew Fleischman</category><category> Brian Ross</category><category> Clint Rucker</category><category> Gwen Keyes Fleming</category><category> John C. Floyd III</category><category> Fani Willis</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>regional politics </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Pulls Back From Humanitarian Cooperation at U.N.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>莫斯科结束叙利亚援助走廊并可能阻止更新黑海粮食协议<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057849"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817814?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">外交官和分析人士表示，俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京似乎愿意打破粮食协议等协议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历山大·卡扎科夫/克里姆林宫/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057849"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mauldin" itemprop="url" rel="author">威廉·莫尔丁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-pulls-back-from-humanitarian-cooperation-at-u-n-a871ae5d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>西方官员表示，由于克里姆林宫在乌克兰面临着一场艰难的战斗，并且在最近国内不稳定的情况下渴望获得国内的支持，俄罗斯准备结束其在联合国关键人道主义领域的合作。</p><p>官员们表示，最近几周，俄罗斯一直在推动从马里撤走联合国维和行动，封锁了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-vetoes-u-n-measure-on-cross-border-aid-to-northern-syria-11657301536?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">联合国对叙利亚的一条重要援助供应线</a>，现在还威胁要终止一项允许乌克兰恢复<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-history-museum-in-recaptured-ukrainian-city-28746610?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">黑海谷物出口的</a>协议。</p><p>莫斯科在联合国重新进行赤裸裸的外交努力之际，俄罗斯正面临一场看不到尽头的乌克兰战争，几周前瓦格纳集团发生了武装叛乱，这对俄罗斯总统构成了十多年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-turmoil-shows-a-forever-war-in-ukraine-hurts-putin-5cbb8738?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最严重的挑战</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>对权力的掌控。</p><p>美俄关系分析师迪米特里·西姆斯表示：“俄罗斯精英和广大俄罗斯民众认为，政府做出了太多让步，而他们却没有得到太多回报。”粮食交易定于周一结束。</p><p>去年7月在伊斯坦布尔签署的黑海粮食倡议是战争期间为数不多的外交突破之一，使乌克兰能够向世界各地出口超过3200万吨小麦、玉米、葵花籽油和其他商品。该协议在黑海开辟了一条特别的海上走廊，供联合国使用商船和包租船将乌克兰粮食运送到苏丹、也门和索马里等受危机影响的国家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817812?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷物在乌克兰港口装载。粮食协议是战争期间为数不多的外交突破之一。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德鲁·克拉夫琴科/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国官员和西方外交官表示，土耳其政府与联合国一起帮助促成了最初的协议，过去一年里，土耳其政府在阻止俄罗斯违反协议方面发挥了核心作用。土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安最近几周再次表达了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkeys-double-dealing-in-the-ukraine-war-345dbfdf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与西方合作的意愿</a>，同意在长达一年的僵局后为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-races-to-secure-turkish-support-for-nato-bid-2452c14f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">瑞典加入北约开绿灯</a>。</p><p>埃尔多安周五表示，他和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkeys-economic-troubles-force-erdogan-to-tilt-away-from-putin-9006b5a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">普京在延长协议方面意见“一致”</a> ，但没有详细说明。克里姆林宫发言人德米特里·佩斯科夫告诉记者，莫斯科仍在权衡这个问题。</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯周五在印度尼西亚雅加达举行的一次集会上表示：“如果莫斯科兑现其威胁，包括该地区在内的发展中国家将付出代价，包括食品价格上涨和粮食短缺加剧。”</p><p>俄罗斯过去曾威胁要取消该协议，并在去年10月乌克兰袭击其驻克里米亚军队后短暂中止了与该协议的合作。乌克兰和美国官员表示，他们担心俄罗斯越来越愿意退出该协议，因为普京在国际上日益孤立，国内不稳定。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>联合国安理会成员国应该如何与俄罗斯在全球问题上合作？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>一位美国官员表示，克里姆林宫可能正在评估粮食协议的成本和收益转移，越来越多的人担心，对乌克兰施加的经济压力可能会超过终止协议的外交影响，特别是在俄罗斯国内存在不确定性的情况下。</p><p>联合国秘书长安东尼奥·古特雷斯上周写信给普京，提议乌克兰继续出口粮食，以换取俄罗斯农业银行的一家子公司与环球银行间金融合作银行国际支付系统重新连接。</p><p>在纽约，俄罗斯几十年来一直利用其作为联合国安理会五个拥有否决权的成员国之一的影响力向西方和其他反对者施加压力，但外交官和分析人士表示，普京现在似乎异常愿意打破过去的协议例如粮食协议和叙利亚援助生命线。</p><p> “俄罗斯已经从脾气暴躁的迁就姿态转变为全面阻挠，”监测冲突的非营利组织国际危机组织的联合国主任理查德·高恩说。</p><p>俄罗斯驻联合国代表团没有回复置评请求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817816?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">二月份，卡车满载联合国向叙利亚提供的物资。俄罗斯最近封锁了联合国对该国的援助供应线。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ghaith Alsayed/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>俄罗斯于 7 月 11 日否决了联合国安理会一项决议，该决议要求人道主义组织向叛军控制的叙利亚境内超过 400 万人提供食品、水和药品。俄罗斯表示不愿就这一问题进行谈判达成妥协，并敦促联合国接受叙利亚政府的提议，要求其控制土耳其的援助运送。</p><p>如果联合国接受这一提议，这将有效地结束近十年来的努力，通过这一努力，该国际机构能够在不寻求大马士革批准的情况下向叙利亚叛军控制的地区提供援助。叙利亚总统巴沙尔·阿萨德长期以来一直试图切断对该国反对派控制地区的粮食和其他供应，试图剥夺叛乱分子的民众支持。</p><p>华盛顿战略与国际研究中心高级研究员娜塔莎·霍尔表示，普京正在“提醒世界，如果他愿意，他可以让世界着火”。</p><p>写信给 Jared Malsin <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(jared.malsin@wsj.com)</a>和 William Mauldin ( <a href="mailto:william.mauldin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">william.mauldin@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/Russia-pulls-back-from-人道主义-合作-at-un-a871ae5d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/Russia-pulls-back-from-人道主义-合作-at-un-a871ae5d<author><![CDATA[Jared MalsinWilliam Mauldin]]></author><category>乌克兰危机</category><category>食品/饮料</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>消费品</category><category>食物产品</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>发展/人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>乌克兰危机</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>发展</category><category>人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>食物</category><category>饮料</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>消费品</category><category>食物产品</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Global Migration Boom Keeps Housing Costs High]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>移民激增正在推高租金并支撑房价，使通胀逃亡变得更加复杂<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057457"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815812?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">截至 6 月份的 12 个月内，澳大利亚主要城市的平均租金上涨了 11.5%。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Brent Lewin/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057457"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stuart-condie" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯图尔特·康迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 15 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>悉尼——富裕国家的移民浪潮正在增加住房成本的上行压力，令租房者和购房者感到沮丧，并使央行官员更难抑制通胀。</p><p>从欧洲到亚洲和北美，受劳动力市场紧张和新冠疫情后宽松的旅行规定的吸引，人们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-biggest-economies-cautiously-open-their-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-664c3549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">跨境流动的人数创历史新高</a>。许多人登陆住房供应短缺的城市。</p><p>尽管借贷成本急剧上升，尤其是在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canadas-immigration-problem-not-enough-homes-for-newcomers-11665144002" target="_blank" class="icon none">欧洲、加拿大和澳大利亚</a>，这有助于推高租金并防止房价下跌至预期水平。</p><p>加拿大去年吸收了创纪录的 437,000 名移民，房价在连续 10 个月下跌后，从 2 月份开始再次上涨。在英国，5 月份的年度租金通胀率达到 2016 年有记录以来的最高水平，并且在过去 21 个月中有 20 个月加速增长。</p><p>在美国， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">租金增长正在放缓</a>，但房价在过去一年下跌后又开始上涨。根据全国房地产经纪人协会的数据，美国现有房屋销售价格中位数在 1 月份触底至 361,200 美元，此后每个月都在上涨，但仍同比下降。</p><p>租金和住房成本<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/inflations-fall-from-a-four-decade-high-in-four-charts-b8612f5f?mod=hp_major_pos2#cxrecs_s" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">仍然是美国通胀的推动因素</a>，占 6 月份消费者价格上涨 0.2% 的 70%。</p><p>许多因素，包括新房供应投资不足，以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/low-mortgage-rates-home-sales-low-supply-899aab29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">一些业主不愿出售</a>，都导致美国住房成本居高不下。不过，一些经济学家表示，如此多的合法和非法移民的到来也是原因之一。去年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-population-growth-remains-sluggish-despite-uptick-this-year-11671723045" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">美国人口增长</a>了 126 万人，这是自 2019 年以来最快的增速，其中几乎全部增长（100 万人）都来自移民。</p><p>高盛最近的一份报告指出，移民是主要经济体房价在加息引发的下跌后出现稳定迹象且高于预期的一个关键原因。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815817?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在加拿大，房地产价格在连续 10 个月下跌后，于 2 月份再次开始上涨。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：格雷厄姆休斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>经济学家约瑟夫·布里格斯（Joseph Briggs）和乔瓦尼·皮尔多梅尼科（Giovanni Pierdomenico）写道：“疫情后移民的复苏似乎正在促进人口增长，从而提高住房需求并限制房价下跌。”他们写道，澳大利亚和加拿大的房价涨幅最大，这两个国家的移民和人口增长反弹最为强劲。</p><p>对于业主和房东来说，移民的支持是个好消息，可以限制经济增长放缓带来的负面影响。住房成本大幅下降（如果利率持续攀升，这种情况仍有可能发生）将破坏世界经济的稳定。</p><p>但对许多人来说，持续居高不下的住房成本令人沮丧，尤其是在许多其他费用不断上涨的情况下。</p><p>斯科特·威尔逊 (Scott) 和黛安·威尔逊 (Dianne Wilson) 与两个年幼的儿子最终决定带着两个年幼的儿子从英国搬到澳大利亚布里斯班，威尔逊女士在那里找到了一名儿童保育教育工作者的工作，他们目睹了 2023 年租金的上涨。他们希望在 8 月份搬家，并考虑每月支付 2,000 美元购买一套家庭住宅，他们的搬迁代理告诉他们，去年的费用约为 1,400 美元。</p><p> “大部分的内容都已经非常非常过时了。我只能将它们描述为 20 世纪 70 年代的风格，”Wilson 说道，并引用了配有牛油果绿色台面的厨房。这对夫妇正在网上搜索犯罪统计数据，以确定更便宜但仍然宜居的社区。</p><p>由于住房成本（尤其是租金）构成央行通胀指标的重要组成部分，其粘性为进一步加息的论点增添了支撑。</p><p>澳大利亚和加拿大央行最近的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-canada-lifts-interest-rates-warns-path-to-stable-inflation-at-risk-18462fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">加息令投资者感到惊讶</a>。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》最近报道，去年移居富裕国家的人数比离开富裕国家的人数多了约 500 万人，比疫情前的水平增加了 80%。德国、加拿大、日本和其他国家正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/even-japan-wants-more-foreign-workers-and-it-is-letting-them-stay-for-good-3628a145?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">重写移民规则</a>，以引进更多人才来填补技能短缺。</p><p>经济学家估计，大约 85% 的移民在抵达一个国家后成为租户，这意味着他们对住房成本的压力在租赁市场上是最大的，尽管有些人最终还是购买了住房。</p><p>澳大利亚在疫情期间基本上关闭了边境，根据官方预测，截至 6 月的 12 个月内，抵达澳大利亚的人数比离开的人数多了约 40 万人，几乎是疫情前平均水平的两倍。官员们预计，截至 2024 年 6 月的 12 个月内，这个人口约 2600 万的国家将新增 315,000 名移民。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815815?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">菲利普·洛 (Philip Lowe)，澳大利亚储备银行行长</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：希拉里·沃德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>随着移民寻找住处，大量涌入促使澳大利亚央行行长菲利普·洛(Philip Lowe)在五月份对通货膨胀发出警报。</p><p>根据房地产分析提供商 CoreLogic 的数据，截至 6 月份的 12 个月里，澳大利亚主要城市的平均租金上涨了 11.5%，比疫情前的水平上涨了 25% 以上。房价在截至 2 月份的七个月里下跌 9.1% 后，最近又开始环比上涨。</p><p> “今年人口增长了 2%。还有2%的房子吗？不，”洛说。</p><p>澳大利亚房地产经纪人表示，最近看房的队伍常常排得很长，以至于许多潜在的租户甚至还没进去就走开了。他们预计，随着北半球学年结束后海外学生的到来，房地产需求将再次激增。</p><p> “我真的不知道要把它们安置在哪里，”在悉尼从事房地产工作的戴安娜·韦西奥 (Diana Vescio) 说。</p><p>韦西奥表示，一些房东提高了租金，以弥补疫情最严重时损失的资金。他回忆起一段时期，一些租户违约、协商降低租金或搬到更便宜的地方。她说，其他人正在努力偿还住房贷款，但住房贷款的成本已经增加。</p><p>当澳大利亚储备银行于 2022 年 5 月开始大幅加息计划时，许多经济学家预计澳大利亚房价将下跌 20%。</p><p>相反，在许多移民的登陆点悉尼，房价从近期低点上涨了 6.7%，相当于住宅价值中位数上涨了 45,000 澳元。</p><p>根据澳大利亚房地产分类集团 Domain 的数据，截至 2024 年 6 月的 12 个月里，悉尼的平均房价可能会上涨 6-9%，因为很少有人出售自己的房子，而且该市的人口在增长。报告预测，在澳大利亚各地，移民将推动对 30 万套住房的需求增加。</p><p>移民给住房供应带来的额外压力可能意味着，自 2022 年 5 月以来已将国家现金利率提高 4 个百分点至 11 年来最高水平的储备银行将继续加息。</p><p>汇丰银行(HSBC)经济学家保罗·布洛克瑟姆(Paul Bloxham)表示，“风险在于，这可能会引发通货膨胀，导致货币环境比其他情况更紧缩。”</p><p>在移民增加和建设缓慢的背景下，德国的租金也在上涨。乌克兰战争造成的超过 110 万难民涌入，导致 2022 年净移民人数达到创纪录的 150 万，而政府每年计划建造 40 万套新公寓，以解决住房短缺问题，而该国的建设比例还不到 75%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815818?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">许多经济学家表示，最好的应对措施是加强建设。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛丽亚·费克/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>房地产平台 ImmoScout24 的数据显示，2023 年第一季度德国的年租金增长加速，柏林和斯图加特的季度增长创下历史新高。报告称，该国七个最大城市的租金上涨导致许多潜在租户被迫迁往周边地区。</p><p>许多经济学家认为，最好的应对措施是加强建设。在英国，新建住房供应量于 2020 年达到顶峰，此后一直未能达到政府每年 30 万套新房的目标，部分原因是大流行造成的破坏。</p><p>澳大利亚政府五月份表示，将很快推出税收减免措施，以增加出租住宿的供应，同时提高对低收入群体的租金援助金额。</p><p>但建设可能需要数年时间，部分原因是严格的规划法规。</p><p>写信给 Stuart Condie： <a href="mailto:stuart.condie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stuart.condie@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f<author><![CDATA[Stuart Condie]]></author><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>房屋销售/住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>房屋销售</category><category>住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Canada Woos American H-1B Visa Holders Fed Up With U.S. Immigration System]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>向外国人提供工作许可证的举措抓住了科技行业的挫败感<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055729"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816894?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加拿大提议的工作许可证将允许 H-1B 签证持有者在没有工作的情况下移居该国。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡洛斯·奥索里奥/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055729"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michelle-hackman" itemprop="url" rel="author">米歇尔·哈克曼 (Michelle Hackman)</a></span> ，华盛顿；保罗·维埃拉 ( <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paul Vieira)</a></span> ，渥太华</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 15 日上午 8:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-u-s-immigration-system-5f7e866d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>本月，加拿大将开始向所有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-layoffs-hit-h1b-visa-workers-hard-ca03c2cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">持有 H-1B 签证的美国移民</a>提供开放工作许可证，此举显然是为了吸引因美国移民程序而受挫的受过高等教育的外国人。</p><p> It is the latest effort by Canada to capitalize on a growing sense from international students and professionals that settling permanently in the US—between evermore competitive visa lotteries and a growing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-other-immigration-morass-a-battle-over-workers-green-cards-11567828860?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">backlog of green cards</a> —is too slow and difficult.</p><p>加拿大上个月在多伦多举行的北美科技会议 Collision 上公布了新的招聘战略，旨在吸引在美国失业的外国科技行业工人，这些工人的移民身份在<a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Ftech-layoffs-hit-h1b-visa-workers-hard-ca03c2cd&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AOvVaw2MMlxA7QeVZdSSGl-wxWnb" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">经历了</a>加拿大移民部长肖恩·弗雷泽表示， <a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Ftech-layoffs-hit-h1b-visa-workers-hard-ca03c2cd&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AOvVaw2MMlxA7QeVZdSSGl-wxWnb" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">最近发生了一系列裁员</a>。</p><p>几十年来，就读美国大学并在美国永久定居一直是全球许多雄心勃勃的年轻外国人的圣杯。但这条老路已经开始磨损。国际学生可以凭学生签证工作一到三年，但此后转为工作签证（最常见的是高技能外国人的 H-1B）最近变得更具竞争力。去年，大约五分之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-says-some-companies-cheat-h-1b-lottery-driving-record-applications-1a3e4fd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的年度 H-1B 抽签</a>申请获得了签证；今年这个数字接近十分之一。</p><p>美国前外交官、Argo Visa 联合创始人克里斯·理查森 (Chris Richardson) 表示：“随着 H-1B 抽签情况逐年恶化，对于许多人来说，加拿大实际上可能是他们唯一的选择。”申请人的美国签证流程。</p><p>加拿大提议的工作许可证将允许 H-1B 签证持有者在没有工作的情况下移居加拿大，并在抵达后寻找工作。加拿大专家表示，符合该计划资格的移民类型也可能很快成为该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/report-cites-canadas-immigration-system-as-role-model-11565701200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">积分移民制度</a>下的永久居民。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6E29A9EF-6E10-45CB-BB21-F8C28BC8FA84&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcanada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-u-s-immigration-system-5f7e866d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">席卷科技行业的裁员也未能幸免持有临时签证（即 H1B）的工人。在被迫离开该国之前，他们只有 60 天的时间寻找新的签证担保职位。主持人佐伊·托马斯 (Zoe Thomas) 与一名面临这一挑战的工人以及《华尔街日报》记者陈德平 (Te-Ping Chen) 讨论了更广泛的影响。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>如果没有快速通道计划，他们要么需要根据加拿大的常规程序申请入境，要么需要加拿大雇主为他们获得工作许可证。</p><p>弗雷泽在会上表示，这种情况为加拿大提供了机会。</p><p> “有很多人在他们的职业生涯中可能没有考虑过来加拿大，但非常想留在北美市场，”他说。</p><p>从英国到澳大利亚的英语国家都受益于外国人对缓慢且看似反复无常的美国移民制度的不满， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/border-arrests-have-dropped-70-since-title-42-ended-biden-administration-says-3d00dc48?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">从英国到澳大利亚的大学</a>都吸引了更多来自中国和印度等国家的国际学生。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>美国如何才能在吸引和留住受过高等教育的外国人方面更好地与加拿大竞争？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>研究移民趋势的移民律师、加拿大官员和政策分析师表示，加拿大被认为是理想的目的地，因为根据过去 15 年修订的规定，国际学生毕业后可以更轻松地获得永久居留权。如果他们最终为美国公司工作，他们可以与同事生活在同一时区。近年来，越来越多的美国公司，如微软、谷歌等，在多伦多、温哥华等加拿大城市设立了分支机构。</p><p>对于从印度到美国的移民来说，他们在科技公司招聘的人员中所占比例过高， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-100-000-green-cards-at-risk-of-going-to-waste-in-covid-19-backlog-11628080201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">成为永久居民的过程</a>被证明是特别令人烦恼的。这是因为美国限制了向任何一种国籍的申请人颁发的就业担保绿卡的数量，而每年申请绿卡的印度人数量远远多于可供他们使用的绿卡数量。如果没有国会的干预，新申请永久居留权的印度人可能会在叫号之前死亡。</p><p> Ketaki Desai 于 2002 年移居美国攻读博士学位。她拥有生物医学科学博士学位，并于 2008 年首次与丈夫申请绿卡。到 2020 年，绿卡仍未获得批准，而且由于新冠病毒相关的处理延误，她现有的签证即将到期。德赛受够了，辞去了在匹兹堡大学医学中心帮助管理 10 亿美元生命科学基金的工作，举家搬到了多伦多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816898?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ketaki Desai 和她的丈夫在多伦多的家中。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：凯塔基·德赛</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“我感到非常沮丧和愤怒，”德赛回忆道。 “当我们意识到我们可以从加拿大永久居留权开始时，这是理所当然的。”</p><p>她在安大略省运营的一家初创基金担任高管，一年前，她离开公司，创办了自己的科技公司，为有特殊需要的儿童开发数字工具。今年，她和她的家人将成为加拿大公民。</p><p>华盛顿智囊团美国政策国家基金会对加拿大移民数据的分析显示，过去十年印度向加拿大的移民数量几乎翻了两番。</p><p>鉴于劳动力老龄化，加拿大正在做出更广泛的努力，利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canadas-immigration-problem-not-enough-homes-for-newcomers-11665144002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">移民作为经济工具</a>来填补整个经济领域的职位空缺，并推动经济增长。加拿大科技行业领导者估计，从软件工程师到编码员再到计算机科学家，明年的工人短缺人数可能达到 25 万人。</p><p>加拿大科技公司贸易组织加拿大创新者委员会主席本杰明·伯根表示：“政府正在尝试利用所有可以利用的手段来缩小这一差距。”</p><p>为了吸引未来的科技行业工人，加拿大最近提供的另一个胡萝卜是让外国学生更容易成为永久居民。自2008年以来，加拿大对移民规则进行了修改，其中包括允许国际学生毕业后获得三年期工作许可证，并在学年和假期期间在校外工作，无需许可证。当时，加拿大官员表示，目标是留住外国毕业生，因为他们熟悉加拿大社会以及对经济的潜在贡献。</p><p>结果是：加拿大学院和大学的国际学生入学人数激增。根据加拿大统计局的数据，2000年，加拿大有122,000名学习许可持有者。加拿大统计局的最新数据显示，这一数字已激增至约 620,000 人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="457" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816880?width=700&amp;height=457" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">蒙特利尔麦吉尔大学。近年来，加拿大学院和大学的国际学生入学人数激增。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼尔·斯利姆/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“如果我是美国政府，我会对加拿大基本上吸走美国工人感到非常沮丧，”多伦多移民律师塞尔吉奥·卡拉斯(Sergio Karas)说，他与公司合作，帮助确保海外工人的安全。</p><p>但加拿大在一个领域还无法竞争：工资。任仕达的一项分析显示，虽然技术人员的工资高于全国平均水平，但与美国类似职位的员工获得的薪酬相比，还是相形见绌，而且许多加拿大技术工人最终离开加拿大，到国外寻找更高薪的职位。一家全球人力资源咨询公司。</p><p>目前，许多离开美国前往加拿大的移民认为这是暂时的举动。</p><p> “对于科技工作者来说，美国是圣杯。更多的钱，更多的可能性，更多的一切。卡拉斯说，就大型跨国公司的机会而言，加拿大非常有限。</p><p>就连德赛也在考虑返回匹兹堡的选择，即使是持临时签证。</p><p> “我们永远是加拿大人，因为当美国不在时，加拿大就在我们身边，”她说。 “但我们想念匹兹堡的社区。”</p><p>写信给 Michelle Hackman <a href="mailto:michelle.hackman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（michelle.hackman@wsj.com）</a>和 Paul Vieira（ <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-us-immigration-system-5f7e866d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-us-immigration-system-5f7e866d<author><![CDATA[Michelle HackmanPaul Vieira]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>肖恩·弗雷泽</category><category>克里斯·理查森</category><category>本杰明·伯根</category><category>德赛克塔基</category><category>塞尔吉奥·卡拉斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item></channel></rss>